{
  "texts": [
    "In order to obtain a better insight into the superlinear speedup and to explain the inflection point, it is necessary to determine the internal architecture of the computer node.",
    "Each node contains several processors, each processor has its own L1 and L2 cache memories, and the L3 cache memory is shared among several processors within one socket and finally the RAM that is common for all the processors of the node.",
    "The L1 and L2 caches are fast but have small memories, usually in total less than 300 -500 kb, while the L3 cache is much larger, 20 -30 Mb.",
    "When a processor needs specific data, it searches for it in the L1 cache, then in the L2 cache, in the L3 cache, and finally in the RAM.",
    "The access time increases by an order of magnitude while addressing the L3 cache as compared to the L1 cache and addressing the RAM takes much longer (Stengel et al., 2015)."
  ]
}